column2: make getExecutable() generate a platform-specific filename

column3: Hi there,

I'm trying to get the PyCharm IDE running faster on a Jetson Nano (linux-aarch64). Compiling the fsnotifier source with the local GCC is straight-forward enough (integrating the change into the build process is not yet), however NativeFileWatcherImpl.getExecutable() will error out with unsupported platform if it's not one of the specifically encoded platforms. To make this a little more hackable, I have changed the code to give a platform-specific executable name to look for instead. This way, providing fsnotifier-aarch64 on the Jetson Nano should do the trick without further need to change the PyCharm package.
There is room for improvement for sure, like ensuring that you get to know the filename that is wanted, however this is a start.
with best regards
Jens Glathe
idea.log

Status update: I got PyCharm CE to run with patched NativeFileWatcher* classes now (yeah!), however the ant build on the build machine keeps crapping out with some corrupted .class file or other. So I have PyCharm CE 2019.1 (191.6605.12 patched) now running on the Jetson Nano, with fsnotifier-linux-aarch64 and no additional warnings in the idea.log. What do you need from me to qualify for a merge?

Status update: I got the build system to generate the installable packages for IDEA-CE and PyCharm-CE with the patch, also on 191.7141. Adding the binary for the linux package should be doable. There is still libdbm64.so to deal with, looking into it. Will be another patch, though.
Well, this push went completely down the toilet. I had no intention to push other people's work to this branch. No idea how to revert it, I'll close and open a new one.
